SIMPLE: filth
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Filth
<hw>Filth</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧lth)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>filthe</ets>, <ets>ful⟦edh⟧e</ets>, AS. <ets>f⟦ymac⟧l⟦edh⟧</ets>,
fr. <ets>f⟦umac⟧l</ets> foul; akin to OHG. <ets>f⟦umac⟧lida</ets>. See
<er>Foul</er>, and cf. <er>File</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Foul
matter; anything that soils or defiles; dirt; nastiness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything that sullies or defiles the moral
character; corruption; pollution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To purify the soul from the dross and <qex>filth</qex> of sensual
delights.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Filth disease</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a disease
supposed to be due to pollution of the soil or water.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Filthily</ent>⟦br⟧
